{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S3 — OIDC / JWKS JWT verifier\n\n## Why\nJWKS-backed JWT validation is the \"OAuth\" half of the confirmed floor and the generic\n\"plug into any OIDC provider\" path — one verifier covers AWS Cognito, Microsoft Entra ID,\nAuth0, Okta, Keycloak, WorkOS, Google ID tokens, and GitHub Actions OIDC, because they all\npublish a JWKS and issue standard JWTs. It is the single highest-leverage verifier for the\nepic's \"wide variety of environments\" goal.\n\n## What\nAdd a **`JWKSTokenVerifier`** to `src/rebar/_mcp_auth.py`, registered on the composite seam and\nselected via `mcp.auth_strategies` with params `jwks_uri`, `issuer`, `audience`, `algorithms`\n(default `[\"RS256\",\"ES256\"]`), optional `leeway`. Implement with PyJWT (`jwt.PyJWKClient` +\n`jwt.decode`); add `pyjwt[crypto]` to the `[mcp]` extra and pin `mcp>=1.28,<2` in `pyproject.toml`.\nIt validates signature (pinned algorithms), `iss`, `aud`, `exp`/`iat`/`nbf`, maps\n`scope`/`scp`→scopes, and returns an `AccessToken` with the claims.\n\n## Approach & rationale\nUse PyJWT's `PyJWKClient` (JWKS fetch + in-process key cache + `kid` lookup + refetch-on-rotation)\nand `jwt.decode` with an explicit pinned `algorithms` allowlist — PyJWT's documented, mainstream\nJWKS path, and the same shape FastMCP's `JWTVerifier` uses, so we get provider-generic OIDC\nvalidation in ~15 lines on the SDK seam. PyJWT is already a transitive of `mcp`; making it explicit\n(`pyjwt[crypto]`) guarantees the `cryptography` backend for RS/ES verification.\n\n## Scope\nThe JWKS/JWT verifier only, on the S2 seam. Not the introspection/proxy/custom verifiers.\nSubset of the epic. Depends on S2.\n\n## Security\nBoundary-crossing. Hard requirements (RFC 8725 JWT BCP): **algorithm pinning** — reject\n`alg:none` and never derive the algorithm from the token header (blocks the RS256↔HS256\nconfusion attack); mandatory `aud` (RFC 8707) + `iss` + `exp` validation with bounded clock-skew\n`leeway`; **SSRF-safe JWKS fetch** — `jwks_uri` fixed at construction, HTTPS-only, bounded\ntimeout, from trusted config not the token (no attacker-controlled `jku`/`x5u`); JWKS cached with\na bounded TTL and rate-limited refetch on unknown `kid` (key rotation without a refetch-DoS);\nfail-closed on any error.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `pyproject.toml` adds `pyjwt[crypto]` to `[mcp]` and pins `mcp>=1.28,<2`; `make typecheck`\n      resolves the imports.\n- [ ] Unit test (tier: unit against the real verifier; the irreducible boundary — the JWKS HTTP\n      fetch — is a stateful fake serving a locally-generated key set) asserts: a JWT signed by the\n      test key with correct `iss`/`aud` → an `AccessToken` with the expected scopes (observable\n      oracle: returned `AccessToken` fields).\n- [ ] Unit tests assert rejection (returns None) for: wrong `iss`; wrong `aud`; expired `exp`; a\n      token with `alg:none`; and a token whose `alg` is `HS256` signed with the RSA public key as\n      the HMAC secret (the RS/HS confusion attack) — each a distinct negative control.\n- [ ] Unit test asserts key rotation is handled: a token signed by a newly-rotated key validates\n      after the JWKS refetch, using the stateful JWKS fake (observable oracle: 2nd token validates,\n      no unbounded refetch).\n- [ ] Integration test (httpx `ASGITransport`) asserts a valid JWKS-issued token is accepted (200)\n      and an unsigned/garbage bearer is rejected (401) end-to-end through the transport.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass.\n\n## Compatibility\nAdditive verifier; opt-in via `mcp.auth_strategies`. The dependency pin/add is the only\ncross-cutting change, backward-compatible with existing `[mcp]` installs."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784066830295424001,"uuid":"3f99c0bc-622a-4c45-bc23-f6d543709c10"}